    {
      "id": "/page/0/Text/8",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">As compensation for credit risks (see Credit Risk), cat bonds normally offer investors yields that are higher than the risk-free interest rate (e.g., the London interbank offered rate (LIBOR); see Bond). The excess yields spread over the riskfree rate should more than compensate for the expected default rate, since it should also contain risk load for uncertainties associated with the default risk.</p>",
      "page": 225,
      "polygon": [
        [
          74.1873417721519,
          542.6401590457257
